  footnotes: []
english:
  title: 'A Summer''s Day: Immediate Impressions'
  author: Seo Geo-jeong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The rain clears and sunlight gleams upon curtain and rail,
    A light cap and thin robe—the heat grows pale.
    The bamboo shoots rise with purpose, nurtured by the rain,
    The fallen blossoms, weakened, scatter on the wind in vain.

    Long have I abandoned brush and ink to hide my name,
    Weary of the entangling gossip of the world's acclaim.
    The jade censer's fragrance fades as first sleep stirs awake,
    Few guests arrive to visit, yet swallows come for morning's sake.
  footnotes:
    - The poem contrasts natural vitality (bamboo shoots strengthened by rain, swallows returning) with the speaker's chosen withdrawal from public life and literary ambition.
    - The jade censer (寶鴨) refers to an ornamental incense burner, suggesting both refinement and solitude.
    - The work reflects Confucian themes of withdrawal from official life and the tranquility found in solitude and nature.
